## Note Please reach out to me before implementing a change in metadata for the legacy records. In addition to differences between the schema, some liberties were taken with applying Dublin Core and there are some changes in how we want to optimally describe assets moving forward. ## Description The following table shows Dublin Core from the record in this ticket and the complementary Datacite property. The Datacite property will link to the part of the schema 4.4 help document that discusses the specific property. *Some Dublin Core will not map neatly to Datacite. I have noted properties that I'm seeking further input on. I will update the table and notify RDSS when I have gathered more complete information.* | Dublin Core | Datacite | Notes | | :------------- | :------------- | :------------- | | Title | [Title](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-mandatory-properties#3-title) | | | Contributors | [Creator](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-mandatory-properties#2-creator) | In the context of this example, the "contributors" are "creators" of the work. Note that an additional field for "[contributor](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#7-contributor)" in Datacite regards non-authoring contributors of the deposit. | | Issue Date | [PublicationYear](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-mandatory-properties#5-publicationyear) | This is the year the object was published to the repository. Hector has made this automatic for the Describe Form. | | Related Publication | placeholder | HH looking into nuance of this. | | Abstract | [Description](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#17-description), with sub-property [descriptionType](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#17a-descriptiontype); suggest "abstract" from controlled list for sub-property | This will be something to discuss further, because "abstract" is too suggestive of the associated paper's abstract for a depositor to always understand what we are asking for, which is a unique description of the deposited data, code or other object. For the new form and metadata, we want to encourage "Description" to capture this information, but may want to optionally allow a choice of description types, if someone wants to get more specific. Please reach out if you want to talk about this. | | Description | [Description](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#17-description), with sub-property [descriptionType](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#17a-descriptiontype); suggest "other" from controlled list for sub-property | The blurb entered to this field is fine for a supplementary description, though it wouldn't stand as a good description on it's own. If this record didn't also contain the "abstract" then a summary description should be taken from the README (if the submitter is unavailable), because we need a good description that will include searchable terms to be indexed by search engines. Additionally, an end-user shouldn't have to access the README to understand if this deposit is what they are looking for. | | URI |
  • For a DOI minted with Datacite: [Identifier](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-mandatory-properties#1-identifier)
  • For an ARK: [AlternateIdentifier with mandatory sub-property](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#11-alternateidentifier) | Some legacy records may only have an ARK, but new records (and some legacy) will have the DOI minted via Datacite that should be used with Identifier. | | Appears in Collections | Collection Tags | RDOS decided to have collection tags |

comments.body: Mapping relation definitions from DSpace to DataCite can be tricky. In our ongoing curation, we interpret "dc.relation.isreferencedby" from DSpace (see https://wiki.lyrasis.org/display/DSDOC5x/Metadata+and+Bitstream+Format+Registries) as "IsCitedBy" in DataCite. There can be confusion because DataCite also has an "IsReferencedBy" relation, but "IsCitedBy" is the current recommendation, so that is what we use for relations between datasets and their corresponding papers (see https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#12b-relationtype).

@bess Regarding how data should appear in Discovery for the related identifier and its controlled variables, please see this example in Zenodo: [Sample; related identifier and subfield](https://zenodo.org/record/7185360#.Y0gvYlLML0s)

### The image shows a sample record in Zenodo's UI that is using the [(12) RelatedIdentifer](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#12-relatedidentifier) property with a variable from the controlled list in [(12.b) relationType](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#12b-relationtype). 

(Note that [(12.a) relatedIdentifierType](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-recommended-and-optional-properties#12a-relatedidentifiertype) would be inputted to the form because it's a mandatory property when using 12 RelatedIdentifier, but this does not explicitly show on the discovery page. Please see the wireframes for the Describe form for how this set of properties should appear in the Describe form.)

        </creator>
        <creator>
            <creatorName nameType="Personal">Graziano, Michael</creatorName>
            <givenName>Michael</givenName>
            <familyName>Graziano</familyName>
            <nameIdentifier nameIdentifierScheme="ORCID" schemeURI="https://orcid.org">https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7727-3475</nameIdentifier>
        </creator>
    </creators>
    <titles>
        <title>Attention and awareness in the dorsal attention network</title>
    </titles>
    <publisher>Princeton University</publisher>
    <publicationYear>2020</publicationYear>
    <resourceType resourceTypeGeneral="Dataset">Dataset</resourceType>
    <language>en</language>
    <sizes/>
    <formats/>
    <version/>
    <descriptions>
        <description xml:lang="en" descriptionType="Abstract">The attention schema theory (AST) posits a specific relationship between subjective awareness and attention, in which awareness is the control model that the brain uses to aid in the endogenous control of attention. We proposed that the right temporoparietal junction (TPJ) is involved in that interaction between awareness and attention. In previous experiments, we developed a behavioral paradigm in human subjects to manipulate awareness and attention. The paradigm involved a visual cue that could be used to guide a shift of attention to a target stimulus. In task 1, subjects were aware of the visual cue, and their endogenous control mechanism was able to use the cue to help control attention. In task 2, subjects were unaware of the visual cue, and their endogenous control mechanism was no longer able to use it to control attention, even though the cue still had a measurable effect on other aspects of behavior. Here we tested the two tasks while scanning brain activity in human volunteers. We predicted that the right TPJ would be active in relation to the cue in task 1, but not in task 2. This prediction was confirmed. The right TPJ was active in relation to the cue in task 1; it was not measurably active in task 2; the difference was significant. In our interpretation, the right TPJ is involved in a complex interaction in which awareness aids in the control of attention.</description>
    </descriptions>
</resource>

        <description descriptionType="Abstract">Helical cell shape is necessary for efficient stomach colonization by Helicobacter pylori, but the molecular mechanisms for generating helical shape remain unclear. We show that the helical centerline pitch and radius of wild-type H. pylori cells dictate surface curvatures of considerably higher positive and negative Gaussian curvatures than those present in straight- or curved-rod bacteria. Quantitative 3D microscopy analysis of short pulses with either N-acetylmuramic acid or D-alanine metabolic probes showed that cell wall growth is enhanced at both sidewall curvature extremes. Immunofluorescence revealed MreB is most abundant at negative Gaussian curvature, while the bactofilin CcmA is most abundant at positive Gaussian curvature. Strains expressing CcmA variants with altered polymerization properties lose helical shape and associated positive Gaussian curvatures. We thus propose a model where CcmA and MreB promote PG synthesis at positive and negative Gaussian curvatures, respectively, and that this patterning is one mechanism necessary for maintaining helical shape.</description>

See the README.txt for detailed description of the strains and conditions represented in each data file.</description>
